                            Kailashtilla gas field is one of the largest gas fields in Bangladesh with six wells. It has been producing gas since 1983. Most of the reserve estimations are based on geological data and production data only used for flowing material balance. But in this study, production data is used for decline curve analyses which also include decline type curves that are useful for reserve estimation at any time of reservoir life. Methods that used for this analysis are: Traditional decline curve, Blasingame, Normalized pressure integral, Transient analysis, and flowing material balance for reserve estimation and skin, permeability calculation. A single method is not possible to apply perfectly for each of well which are grouped in total four gas sand (upper, middle, lower & HRZ). Lower gas sand is abandoned after long time production which is not included for final EUR calculation.

                            This study estimates mainly gas initially in place (GIIP), recoverable reserves, and recovery factor of Kilashtilla gas field. The result of calculation shows that GIIP is about 3.1 Tcf, recoverable reserves is about 2.03 Tcf and recovery factor is 74%. Also this analysis suffers from liquid loading problem and may presence of aquifer or partially fault.
